## 1. Variables, Input & Output

**Python docs:** [Input and Output](https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/inputoutput.html) | [Built-in Functions (input, print)](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html) | [Formatted string literals](https://docs.python.org/3/reference/lexical_analysis.html#formatted-string-literals)

### a. Variables and types

**Definition:** *A variable is a labeled box — the label is the name, the contents are the value. In system design, variables map to entity attributes (User.name, User.email), config key-value pairs, and environment variables that inject runtime values.*

**Syntax:**
```
variable_name = value
age = 25
name = "Alice"
price = 19.99
```

| Item | Location |
|------|----------|
| Concept | `practice_python/python.py` |
| Example | `python_programe_cs50/hello.py`, `name.py` |

**Note:** In system design, variables map to entity attributes — e.g., User entity has `name`, `email`, `user_id`. Config stores key-value pairs; environment variables inject runtime values. Naming is the first step of data modeling.

### b. User input

**Definition:** *`input()` pauses and returns user input as a string. Conversion (`int`, `float`) enforces type. In system design, input is the API boundary — REST request body/query params serve the same role; schema validation (Pydantic, JSON Schema) enforces types at the boundary.*

**Syntax:**
```
user_input = input("Prompt: ")
number = int(user_input)
decimal = float(user_input)
```

**Note:** Input is the API boundary for CLI apps. In REST APIs, request body/query params serve the same role — raw strings that must be validated and parsed. Schema validation (Pydantic, JSON Schema) enforces types at the boundary.

### c. Formatted output (f-strings)

**Definition:** *An f-string is a template with holes — Python fills in the blanks. In system design, string templating appears in log formatting, email templates, and API response construction; structured logging (JSON) and i18n templates are alternatives.*

**Syntax:**
```
f"Hello, {name}"
f"Price: ${price:.2f}"
```

**Syntax variations (same result, different style):**
```python
name = "Alice"
print(f"Hello, {name}")           # f-string
print("Hello, {}".format(name))   # .format()
print("Hello, %s" % name)         # %
print("Hello, " + name)           # concatenation
```

**Output:** (all produce)
```
Hello, Alice
```

**Note:** In system design, string templating appears in log formatting, email templates, API response construction. Structured logging (JSON) avoids format strings; user-facing messages use i18n templates.

