## 5. Lists

**Python docs:** [Lists](https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/introduction.html#lists) | [Sequence Types (list)](https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#sequence-types-list-tuple-range)

### a. Creating and appending

**Definition:** *A list is an ordered, mutable sequence. Empty `[]`, append with `.append()`. In system design, lists model ordered collections — event logs (append-only), job queues (FIFO), audit trails. Message queues (Kafka, SQS) are distributed lists; order matters for replay and causality.*

**Syntax:**
```
lst = []
lst = [1, 2, 3]
lst.append(4)
```

| Item | Location |
|------|----------|
| Concept | `practice_python/list_sum.py`, `list_numbers_avg.py` |
| Example | `python_programe_cs50/students.py`, `names.py` |

**Note:** In system design, lists model ordered collections — event logs (append-only), job queues (FIFO), audit trails. Message queues (Kafka, SQS) are distributed lists. Order matters for replay and causality.

### b. Indexing and slicing

**Definition:** *0-based indexing; `lst[-1]` is last element. Slicing `lst[start:end]` returns sublist.*

**Syntax:**
```
lst[0]
lst[-1]
lst[1:4]
```

**Note:** Indexing is O(1) for lists. In distributed systems, partition keys often derive from list index (e.g., shard_id = user_id % num_shards). Slicing is used for pagination (offset/limit).

### c. Sorting and aggregation

**Definition:** *`sorted(lst)` returns new list; `lst.sort()` mutates in place. `sum()`, `len()` aggregate.*

**Syntax:**
```
sorted(lst)
lst.sort()
sum(lst)
len(lst)
```

**Note:** Sorting is O(n log n). In data pipelines, sort-merge join requires sorted inputs. Aggregation (sum, count, avg) is the core of analytics; in distributed systems, map-reduce aggregates across partitions.

