## 8. Sets

**Python docs:** [Sets](https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/datastructures.html#sets) | [Set Types (set, frozenset)](https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#set-types-set-frozenset)

### a. Unique elements

**Definition:** *A set stores unique elements with O(1) membership test. In system design, sets model unique constraints — user IDs seen, tags, allowed roles. Bloom filters approximate set membership for large data; Redis SET, DynamoDB GSI. Deduplication in streams uses set-like structures.*

**Syntax:**
```
s = {1, 2, 3}
s = set([1, 2, 2, 3])
s.add(4)
x in s
```

| Item | Location |
|------|----------|
| Concept | `practice_python/set_numbers_sort.py`, `set_string_sort.py` |
| Example | `python_programe_cs50/houses.py` |

**Note:** In system design, sets model unique constraints — user IDs seen, tags, allowed roles. Bloom filters approximate set membership for large data. Redis SET type; DynamoDB GSI with unique attribute. Deduplication in streams uses set-like structures.

### b. Unordered collection

**Definition:** *Sets don't guarantee order. Use `sorted(s)` for ordered output.*

**Syntax:**
```
sorted(s)
sorted(s, reverse=True)
```

**Note:** Order is sacrificed for O(1) lookup. In distributed systems, maintaining global order is expensive; sets avoid that. For "distinct count" queries, HyperLogLog approximates set cardinality without storing elements.

### c. Deduplication

**Definition:** *`list(set(lst))` removes duplicates. Order is lost.*

**Syntax:**
```
unique = list(set([1, 2, 2, 3, 3]))
```

**Output:**
```
[1, 2, 3]   # order may vary
```

**Note:** Deduplication is common in ETL (idempotent loads), event processing (exactly-once semantics), and log aggregation. Kafka uses offsets; idempotent consumers use seen-IDs set.

